ice Haggerty, Glendive.\nMont J. A. Matterson, Mr. Smith.\nGreeley. Colo\ni Johnson\u2014 Burrell Cole, llorlder,\nColo B. W Hundley. Denver; Tom\nDegney, Jelin; W. P. Peak, Cheyenne.\nCARLOAD RECEIPTS\nAT FREIGHT STATION\nOutgoing rarload receipt! at the\nfreight station yesterday includes two\ncars of plaster, 56 cars of Ice,, one\ncar of company material and 19 can\nof ties.\nr 1W EAKAME REPUBUCAN-DAEB HXTIOR.\nMS\nPHASING\nFIRST NUMBER OF ARTISTS\u2019\nCOURSE RECEIVED WITH\nMUCH PLEASURE HERE\nDelbert O. Lean, dramatic \"reader of\nunusual talent, gave an entertsinment\nbefore a rather small but very appre\nciative audience last evening at the\nuniversity auditorium. This was the\nfirst number of the Artists* course, sad\nif the following programs are as al*\ntractive the course will surely be a\ngreat success. Although it is realized\nthat but short time was given for ad\nvertising this first number, one won\nders why the atendance was not larg\ner, and before another number it is to\nbe hoped that all the people of Lara\nmie will have been reached.\nDoan Faville, a former college class\nmate of Mr. l>ean, introduced him\nwith some humurous remarks about\nwhat he could tell about his college\ndays if he were not afraid of Mr. Lean\nhaving the last word. Mr. Lean has\nalways shown a talent for the pro\nsession he Is now following and back\nin his school dava was counted among\nthe best the college afforded as an\nentertainer.\nOpening bia program with a read\ning from Joseph Lincoln's \u201cCaptain\nEll\u201d he Included an Interesting vari\nclty of numbers selected from the mod\nem and the old school. Perhaps re\nquiring the greatest artistry was ren\ndition of the scene from Midsummer\nNight\u2019s Dream In which the trades\nmen rehearse for the play which they\nplan to present at the dukes wedding\ncelebration. The scene brings in a\nnumber of characters, and Mr. Lean\nportrayed them all with a whimsical\nmanner which won great favor with\nhis audience.\nAnother favorite selection was the\nreading from Captain Eli, with the\nIntroduction of three old sea captains,\nand a humurous account of their strug\ngles to acquire a wife as housekeeper.\nConcluding the program were the\nChristmas Eve story by Grace Rich\nmond and a poem of country life,\n\u201cWhen the Train Comes fn. A\nMr. Lean, who Is handsome and very\nattractive physically, has a splendid\nvoice, and the stage manner which is\nthe result of many years* acquaintance\nwith public appearance. He is a real\nly remarkable Impersonator, and hie\nrepoitorlre ranges from the humorous\nto thb tear compelling. His natural\nmanner, and the finished in which\nho gave hla readings won many com\npliments from the audience.\nQUALITY GROCERIES.\nFlag Brand Borries, Fruits, Catsup,\nChili Sauce, Feas, Bantam Corn.\nBeane. Absolutely the highest grade\nput up In cane.\nHOGBEN A HARPER,\nGroceries and Freeh Meats.\nWe deliver. Phone 174. llGtt\nSTOLEN\u2014FROM MECCA BIL\nLIARD PARLOR, WEDDING RING\nAND OTHER ARTICLES OF JEW.\nELRY VALUED AS KEEPSAKES.\nLIBERAL REWARD AND NO GUES\nTIONS ABKED IF RETURNED TO\nJAMES BARRY AT THB MECCA.\nNOTICE TO CREDITORS.\nEstate of William Warren Terrell,\ndeceased.\nNotice is hereby given that letters\nof administration were on \u00abho 17th\nday of December 1920. granted to the\nundersigned In the above estate, and\nall persons having claims against the\nsaid estate are hereby required to ex\nhibit them, with the necessary vouch\ners for allowance, to the undersigned\nMartha E. Stickney, within six months\nafter the date of said letters, or they\nmay be precluded from any benefit\nfrom such estate, and if such claims\nbe not exhibited within one year from\ndate of said letters, they will be for\never barred.\nDated December 17, 1920.\nMARTHA E. STICKNEY,\nDec 18-25 Jan 1-8. Administratrix.\nOld papers 25c per hundred at The\nRepublican office.\nw \u2019is\nYOUR BOTTOM DOLLAR.\nyou can bet on our work when we vul\ncanise your worn out tirea.|