Mu wife In March of this year.\nCOURT, 0. K.*S HAIR PULUWG\nWife Justified In -Remmwtratlnflf\nWith Rival. MnmMiutt,\nJud,e Rules.\nLynn, Maas\u2014A talr-pnmnt match\nbetween q wife and another woman\nwho I, fetand with the hnaband la per\nfectly la order from tte spouto', view\npoint, aeeordlnr to Ute rullnr nt An\nwrist, Jmtlce Edward B. t/Brta of\nthe Dlatriet court here.\nHe wan called upon to render a de\nrision at the trial ot Mm Lillian\nMiner, a divorcee, charred with as\nsault with a revolver upon Mm Cath\nerine Curtis, the wife of a Boston po\nliceman. Altbouh It was eharred\nthat Mm Curtis made tte flret move,\nla tte boMUIUm the Justice anld:\n-I think the wife le Juetlfled In re\nmonstratlu, even to the extent of\npulllnr hafr, *ad It such a case came\nbefore UMltar trial I should rule In\nfavor of tit, narrieved wife.\"\nniK.iiataaiieii\nLove of Mutio Traps\nHMborof Poor\u00dfox I\nt \"s\nPhiladelphia.\u2014-It was bls love J\nfor music which led to the ar- S\nrest of Jscob Kata, twenty-four\nyears old. Katz entered the\nEmanuel Lutheran church here\nahortly after midnight and\nfound the paar box which he\nemptied of Its contents, S 3.\nThen he fbund the new organ.\nKats had musical talent and he\nran his Angers over the keys.\nThen be became so absorbed in\nthe fnstrvwat that bo forgot\nwhere te waa. pulled out the\ndlaphnna aad thundered away.\nThe strains awakened the pas\ntor, Rev. Rudolph Nleder, who\nIlves next daor, and te called\ntte police\nROBBER OFFERS VICTIM SlO\n-Yeu Need It Wares Than Ho Says\nta Holdup or Finding Man\nPon\u00dflloaa.\nO.\u2014Daniel Cable, a\npottery worker, reported to the police\nhere that a robber, who bad held him\nup while te waa on his way home In\na suburb, offered to give him SlO after\nthe highwayman discovered that te\nwas penniless.\nCable said that the robber leaped\nupon, overpowered him, and then went\nthrough his pockets. Finding no\nmoney. Cable said, the highwayman\nreached Into his own pocket, pulled\nout a roll of bills and offered to give\nhim SlO, saytag: \u201cHere, brother, yon\nneed It worse than I do.\"\nCable said te waa too surprtood to\naccept the money.\nLaborer Goto\nAnaconda, Mont\u2014From a laborer's\ntask at the Washoe smelter to the\npossession of 8150,000 was the realisa\ntion here recently of Claude Sheuma\nker, who received a telegram from an\nEastern broker advising him ttet he\nhad realized thia fortune oa tte sale\nof oil stock. Bbeumaker Immediately\ndrew his earnings, purchased a rail\nroad ticket and started East Bheu\nmaker conceived tte idea of buying oU\nstock while la tte army. While serv\ning overseas with tte Twenty-third di\nvision he was wounded. His original\ninvestment was 8300 of back army pay.\nHe intends purdbaalng a ranch in Ore\ngon. be said,\nBally tayukUcu ywr.\nHKKHKHH\nm-wuiws\nDo F\nONLY FEW DISCHARGED WHEN\nSOLDIERS RETURN FROM FRONT\nIN SOME LARGE CITIESt\nBy the AaoMtetod Pnoo\nChicago, Jan. B.\u2014Only part of the\nwomen engaged in industry during\nthe war period have lost their places\nthrough the return of mm from the\nwar and the lack of employment Mica\nMary Anderson, director of the wom\nen\u2019s bureau of the United States De\npartmeat of Labor, reports.\n\u201cStatements to the bureau from hun\ndreds of industry heads who employed\nonly women during tbe war show they\nhave retained their female help, while\nothers state they have replaced their\nwomen with male workers,*\u2019 Miss An\nderson said.\n\u201cBecause of the volume of unem\nployment throughout the country to\nday no accurate figures as to the\nnumber of women employed in Indus\ntries at present as compared with the\nwar period are obtainable.\nMillions at Work\n\u201cI believe that when figures of the\n1920 census are available, they will\nshow more than U.OOO.cOu women in\ngainful occupation. The census, how\never, will not set forth the present\nsituation because unemployment baa\nincreased by leaps and bounds since\nit waa taken.\n\u201cWomen won Ibe admiration of em\nployers during the war period by their\nability to fill in on men\u2019s jobs. Take\nfor instance lathe operators. Thous\nands of women became very efficient\nand still retain their places beside\nmen operators. The war gave Amer\nican women a new opportunity In in\ndustry and they grasped It.\u201d\nThere are two factors needed to In\nsure women their place in Industry,\nMias Anderson said. Protective legis\nlation for the eight-hour day is badly\nneeded, she declsred, and added that\nthe women must \u201corganize within the\nnext few years.\u201d\nWith the return of prosperity. In\ndustries will clamor for women work\ners, In the opinion of Miss Mary E.\nMcDowell of the University of Chi\ncago Settlement house, who is chatr\nman of the women iu industry com\nmittee of the National League of\nWomen Voters.\ngoodlOr\nCML NNIK 1.;\nCOLORADO MfflES\nBy tbe Associated Pms\nDenver, Colo., Jan. 8. \u2014Nineteen\ntwenty was a record year in the coal\nmining Industry of Colorado. Figures\ncompiled by James Dalrymple coal\nmine inspector, show a state produc\ntion of 12.377.436 tons compared with\n10,274,508 In 1919.\nThis production was reached des\npite tbe fact that the mines in the\nnorthern district were closed twice by\nstrikes and tbe Routt county field\nwas partially shut down for several\nmonths because of a car shortage on\nthe Denver and Salt Lake railroad.\nOs the twenty coal producing coun\nties, Las Animas led with a produc\ntion of 4,310.839 tons and Huerfano\nwas second with 2,423,312. The men\nemployed in the mines totalled 14,295.\nBank Robber Saw* Jail Ban\nand Flee* From N. Y.\nPriaon.\n\u25a0ib M\nHenry L. Bitzberger. twenty-four,\nalleged bank robber, who escaped from\nthe West Side Prison, New York City,\nwhere he was being held to await ex\ntradition to New Jersey on the charge\nof having robbed the Milltown First\nNational Bank at New Brunswick N.\nJ. It was during an exercise period\nthat Bitzberger sawed a bar from\na window seven feet above the uoor,\nbent back the ends, and crawled\nthrough a ten-inch opening. Only thd\ncourage of Keeper George Anton, who\nhalted nineteen prisoners st the point\nof his pistol, prevented a wholesale\njail delivery of men who attempted to\nloUow tte escaped convict.\nRock Springs Lump\nNorth Park Lump\nand\u2019Nut\nxJ--' A.\nCOAL PRICES REDUCED have been reduced, 23 cents a ton\nSEVENTY-FIVE CENTS last week and 50 cento a ten, this.\nTwice within the last few days the making a cut of 73 cento In t|ie prim\nprice of coal at the mines in Wyoming to dealers at the mines.\nWANTED\nSecond Hand Furniture\n\u2014Stoves and Rangos\nLARAMIE FURNITURE CO.,\nWilli* Jensen, Prop.\nREPUBLICAN WANT ADS\nAds in this column bring Result*. They ura one cent a\nword for each insertion. CASH TO ACCOMPANY THp*\nAD. If you have lost anything, have found anything, have\nanything for sale or rent, or, in short, have a want of any kind,\ntry.THE REPUBLICAN WANT COLUMN. The coat is but\nlittle, and the result* are big.\nr\u2014\u25a0\nHELP WANTED\nWANTEfr\u2014Cook and hotnakeeper.\nt\u00bbkoto 12*15\n.WAWMD\u2014MUWIoagfa aromaa oi\nvaodiirifraXxkt lWKwwork. enow\ntoSB.- r-- 12KI\nMISCELLANEOUS\nBOARD and ream lor two gentlemen\n-at- St*- University. -Mra. Alexander.\n!Mt4\nMEN WANTED\u2014Ty qttallfy for fire\nmon, brakemen, experience unneces\nsary. Transportation furnished. Write\nA. Scoles, Supt., Gamble Bldg.. St\nLouis. 3nn\u00df 15-22-29;\nGOOD dressmaking done by the day\nin private home. l\u00bbhone 227 J. 122tt\nPRODUCING Tailoring agents want\ned. Men> Made-to-order suits. Finest\nSpring swatch line ready. Leeds\nWoolen MULm, rhlcago.\nTINNER wants situation. Address\n212 Second street (upstairs). Wm.\nCoagritf. 12613\nMEN WANTED for detective work.\nExperience unnecessary. Write J.\nGan or, former U. S. government de\ntective, Gt. lamils. Jan B-15-22\nKalsomining, paper and\nwindow washing. Work guaranteed.\nPrice right. Dewey Bm*ss. Fulton\nRooms. Phone 1